{"id": "42253", "revid": "58609", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=42253", "title": "Yl'nira", "text": "Yl'nira, the Edge of Temperance, also known as The Last Vestige of the &lt;a href=\"Matyr\"&gt;Matyr&lt;/a&gt; was an &lt;a href=\"angel\"&gt;angel&lt;/a&gt;ic &lt;a href=\"daggers\"&gt;dagger&lt;/a&gt;. \nLore.\nYl'nira was an elegant blade, decorated with delicate inlay and filigree. In the midst of its ornamentation stood a golden hooded figure, peaceful and mysterious, bearing a glittering jewel of pale blue in its arms.\nHistory.\nYl'nira apparently belonged to an &lt;a href=\"archangel\"&gt;archangel&lt;/a&gt;; apparently one of the angels who followed &lt;a href=\"Inarius\"&gt;Inarius&lt;/a&gt; to &lt;a href=\"Sanctuary\"&gt;Sanctuary&lt;/a&gt;. Yl'nira's owner had a &lt;a href=\"nephalem\"&gt;nephalem&lt;/a&gt; child with a &lt;a href=\"demon\"&gt;demon&lt;/a&gt;, and Yl'nira was bequeathed to the child. The dagger was later hidden by &lt;a href=\"the%20Ancients\"&gt;the Ancients&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href=\"Temple%20of%20Namari\"&gt;Temple of Namari&lt;/a&gt;.\nAfter &lt;a href=\"the%20Shard-seeker\"&gt;the Shard-seeker&lt;/a&gt; slew &lt;a href=\"Sargoth\"&gt;Sargoth&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Namari\"&gt;Namari&lt;/a&gt; bequeathed them with the dagger. Back in &lt;a href=\"Westmarch%20%28City%29\"&gt;Westmarch&lt;/a&gt;, the Shard-seeker and &lt;a href=\"Deckard%20Cain\"&gt;Deckard Cain&lt;/a&gt; used Yl'nira to destroy the corrupted &lt;a href=\"Worldstone\"&gt;Worldstone&lt;/a&gt; shards they'd collected.\nIn the &lt;a href=\"Forest%20of%20Misery\"&gt;Forest of Misery&lt;/a&gt;, Yl'nira appeared to the Shard-seeker and prevented their &lt;a href=\"Light\"&gt;Light&lt;/a&gt; from being drained by &lt;a href=\"The%20Old%20Growth\"&gt;The Old Growth&lt;/a&gt;. It then led them to &lt;a href=\"Verathiel\"&gt;rescue&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Mikayel\"&gt;some&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Andalon\"&gt;angels&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Shaddox\"&gt;trapped&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href=\"Realm%20of%20Damnation\"&gt;Realm of Damnation&lt;/a&gt;. However, even after destroying three of the &lt;a href=\"Worldstone\"&gt;Worldstone&lt;/a&gt; shards, the &lt;a href=\"Soul%20Siphon\"&gt;Soul Siphon&lt;/a&gt;s, and the first two &lt;a href=\"Pits%20of%20Anguish\"&gt;Pits of Anguish&lt;/a&gt; were destroyed, &lt;a href=\"Skarn\"&gt;Skarn&lt;/a&gt; was able to steal the blade and bind it to his will with his corruptive power. After it was retrieved, the blade was reduced to dust upon expunging a fourth Worldstone shard.\nIn-game.\nYl'nira features in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20Immortal\"&gt;Diablo Immortal&lt;/a&gt;\", though is not an item in the strictest sense. It appears on the player character's waist during much of the &lt;a href=\"Realm%20of%20Damnation\"&gt;Realm of Damnation&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"quest\"&gt;quest&lt;/a&gt;line."}
{"id": "34749", "revid": "50366882", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=34749", "title": "Ymil", "text": "In the &lt;a href=\"Sahptev\"&gt;Sahptev&lt;/a&gt; faith, Ymil is the god of the rivers, emblematic of emotion, intuition, and the life-giving properties of water. Very few of the &lt;a href=\"Monks%20of%20Ivgorod\"&gt;Monks of Ivgorod&lt;/a&gt; align themselves with this deity, preferring the strength and resolve attributed to deities such as &lt;a href=\"Ytar\"&gt;Ytar&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Zaim\"&gt;Zaim&lt;/a&gt;. Some Monks, most notably &lt;a href=\"Akyev\"&gt;Akyev&lt;/a&gt;, argue that Ymil is a capricious and indecisive god. He is also shown to possess trickery as he once stole some strength from Zaim.\nYmil's domain also partly covers rain."}
{"id": "50831", "revid": "50366882", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=50831", "title": "Ymuthrus", "text": "Ymuthrus was a member of the &lt;a href=\"Inari\"&gt;Inari&lt;/a&gt;. He was the &lt;a href=\"Prevailing%20Wind\"&gt;Prevailing Wind&lt;/a&gt; during the outbreak of the Affliction.\nBiography.\nAfter the theft of the &lt;a href=\"Pathstone\"&gt;Pathstone&lt;/a&gt; by &lt;a href=\"Morwith\"&gt;Morwith&lt;/a&gt;, Ymuthrus became the new &lt;a href=\"Prevailing%20Wind\"&gt;Prevailing Wind&lt;/a&gt; of &lt;a href=\"Ancients%27%20Cradle\"&gt;Ancients' Cradle&lt;/a&gt;. He declared that Morwith had damned their home with her selfishness, and declared that every &lt;a href=\"Lilin\"&gt;Lilin&lt;/a&gt; who had advocated fleeing the Cradle were just as responsible. That their punishment would be &lt;a href=\"death\"&gt;death&lt;/a&gt;. His fellow Inari were taken aback by the severity of his edict, but only one, &lt;a href=\"Zatham\"&gt;Zatham&lt;/a&gt;, spoke out against it.\nYmuthrus insisted Zatham be judged in the rite of &lt;a href=\"Purity%27s%20Penance\"&gt;Purity's Penance&lt;/a&gt;. It did not kill Zatham, but burned the eyes from his face. Ymuthrus then permitted him exile. &lt;a href=\"Geherit\"&gt;Geherit&lt;/a&gt; noted that it was, by Ymuthrus's standards, generous."}
