{"id": "48430", "revid": "2011810", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=48430", "title": "Battle Points", "text": "Battle Points are a way to level up the &lt;a href=\"Battle_Pass%23Diablo_Immortal\"&gt;Battle Pass&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20Immortal\"&gt;Diablo Immortal&lt;/a&gt;\".\nGameplay.\nThere is a weekly limit of 2400 Battle Points from activities. However this limit also resets whenever a new Battle Pass comes out which is on a Thursday, allowing a higher amount of Battle Points to be earned on that week.\nSources.\nActivities:\nQuests unlock every 3 days.\nHistory.\nThe update on changed the weekly Battle Points cap to be cumulative - instead of the points resetting to zero on Monday, the cap goes up by 2400, allowing players to catch up."}
{"id": "9282", "revid": "45099015", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=9282", "title": "Battle Rage", "text": "Battle Rage is a Tactics skill. It resembles the &lt;a href=\"Battle%20Command\"&gt;Battle Command&lt;/a&gt; skill from the previous game, but only affects the Barbarian.\nIn-game.\nLike all Tactics skills, Battle Rage is an instant cast, and can be used at any time, including while on the move or while performing any other attack. However, unlike &lt;a href=\"Threatening%20Shout\"&gt;Threatening Shout&lt;/a&gt; and , it only affects the Barbarian, and costs &lt;a href=\"Fury\"&gt;Fury&lt;/a&gt; instead of generating it. To compensate for this, this skill is effectively a passive buff to the Barbarian's offensive capabilities, as it has a powerful duration of effect even without the Inspiring Presence passive skill.\nUnlike similar skills of other classes, Tactics shouts are not mutually-exclusive, and may be combined with each other.\nDevelopment.\nIn the days before the pre-expansion patch for \"&lt;a href=\"Reaper%20of%20Souls\"&gt;Reaper of Souls&lt;/a&gt;\", the Into the Fray rune actually provided a chance for the Barbarian's Critical Hits to generate 15 Fury, in addition to any Fury that was already generated by the hit. While it was meant to allow Barbarians a way to deal damage without having to make use of a Primary skill, it ultimately proved too powerful for game balancing reasons, especially when combined with the &lt;a href=\"Wrath%20of%20the%20Berserker\"&gt;Wrath of the Berserker's&lt;/a&gt; Thrive on Chaos rune. With the aforementioned combination in effect, the Barbarian was a virtually \"unstoppable\" force. Nothing short of killing the Barbarian very quickly could put an end to their otherwise very long blood-thirsty reign over the minions of Hell."}
