{"id": "27058", "revid": "24916843", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=27058", "title": "Belphegor (Siege Runekeeper)", "text": "Belphegor was a servant of &lt;a href=\"Diablo\"&gt;Diablo&lt;/a&gt;. During the &lt;a href=\"Eternal%20Conflict\"&gt;Eternal Conflict&lt;/a&gt;, she commanded Diablo's siege demons in an attack against the &lt;a href=\"Pandemonium%20Fortress\"&gt;Pandemonium Fortress&lt;/a&gt;. After the disappearance of the &lt;a href=\"Worldstone\"&gt;Worldstone&lt;/a&gt; and stalling of the &lt;a href=\"Eternal%20Conflict\"&gt;Eternal Conflict&lt;/a&gt;, she apparently remained in &lt;a href=\"Pandemonium\"&gt;Pandemonium&lt;/a&gt;.\nAeons later, she was confronted by &lt;a href=\"the%20Nephalem\"&gt;the Nephalem&lt;/a&gt;, who slew her to obtain a siege rune. In the resulting explosion, all that remained of her was a single hand.\nIn-game.\nBelphegor, Siege Runekeeper is a &lt;a href=\"Super%20Unique\"&gt;Super Unique&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Warscarred%20Ravager\"&gt;Warscarred Ravager&lt;/a&gt; found in &lt;a href=\"Path%20of%20War\"&gt;Path of War&lt;/a&gt; in during &lt;a href=\"The%20Battlefields%20of%20Eternity%20%28Quest%29\"&gt;The Battle Fields of Eternity quest&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\". She attacks alongside a horde of &lt;a href=\"Warscarred%20Marauder\"&gt;Marauders&lt;/a&gt;, Ravagers and &lt;a href=\"Demonic%20Hellflyer\"&gt;Firewings&lt;/a&gt;, and in addition has Plagued, Thunderstorm and Jailer affixes.\nUpon death, she drops the first of the three Siege Runes the player needs to activate &lt;a href=\"the%20Ram\"&gt;the Ram&lt;/a&gt;, and allows talking to &lt;a href=\"Imperius\"&gt;Imperius&lt;/a&gt; to continue the quest."}
{"id": "3238", "revid": "3423357", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=3238", "title": "Belt", "text": "The Belt is a type of &lt;a href=\"Belts\"&gt;Belt&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20II\"&gt;Diablo II&lt;/a&gt;\". The &lt;a href=\"Nightsmoke\"&gt;Nightsmoke&lt;/a&gt; is the &lt;a href=\"Unique%20Items\"&gt;unique&lt;/a&gt; version of the belt."}
{"id": "30986", "revid": "25771421", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=30986", "title": "Belt of Transcendence", "text": "Belt of Transcendence\u00a0is a &lt;a href=\"Legendary%20Items\"&gt;Legendary&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"belts\"&gt;belt&lt;/a&gt; in\u00a0\"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\", added in patch 2.2.0. It requires\u00a0&lt;a href=\"character%20level\"&gt;character level&lt;/a&gt;\u00a031 to drop.\nThe special property causes any damaging hit of any skill that costs &lt;a href=\"Mana\"&gt;Mana&lt;/a&gt; to summon one &lt;a href=\"Fetish%20Sycophant\"&gt;Fetish Sycophant&lt;/a&gt;, working much like the named skill, although Fetish Sycophants will also trigger on primary skills. \nIf the &lt;a href=\"Witch%20Doctor\"&gt;Witch Doctor&lt;/a&gt; does not have this skill, they will, in fact, gain one with this belt, freeing a passive slot. Taking both is useless, since the total limit of 15 Sycophants applies to the skill and to the belt."}
{"id": "30459", "revid": "25771421", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=30459", "title": "Belt of the Trove", "text": "Belt of the Trove is a\u00a0&lt;a href=\"Legendary%20Items\"&gt;Legendary&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0&lt;a href=\"belt\"&gt;belt&lt;/a&gt; in\u00a0\"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\". It requires\u00a0&lt;a href=\"character%20level\"&gt;character level&lt;/a&gt;\u00a060 to drop, and originally only dropped during the &lt;a href=\"Season\"&gt;Season&lt;/a&gt; Two for Seasonal characters. After the end of this Season, it drops for normal characters as well. In patch 2.1.2, it replaced the &lt;a href=\"Ageless%20Might\"&gt;Ageless Might&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe unique affix ignores the &lt;a href=\"cooldown\"&gt;cooldown&lt;/a&gt; of &lt;a href=\"Bombardment\"&gt;Bombardment&lt;/a&gt;, but fully benefits from its runes and enhancements: that is, if the player puts Bombardment into their Action Bar with a rune, Belt of the Trove will use said rune in all of its attacks. Triggering radius is approximately 40 yards. This belt functions even if the &lt;a href=\"Crusader\"&gt;Crusader&lt;/a&gt; does not have the respective skill. \nThis belt is of huge use with &lt;a href=\"Thorns%20of%20the%20Invoker\"&gt;Thorns of the Invoker&lt;/a&gt; set, as it allows permanent damage reduction when in combat."}
{"id": "50140", "revid": "1773829", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=50140", "title": "Belt slot", "text": "Belt slots are spaces where &lt;a href=\"potions\"&gt;potions&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"scrolls\"&gt;scrolls&lt;/a&gt; may be kept in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20%28Game%29\"&gt;Diablo&lt;/a&gt;\" and \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20II\"&gt;Diablo II&lt;/a&gt;\" instead of the main &lt;a href=\"inventory\"&gt;inventory&lt;/a&gt;. Some or all belt slots have number hotkeys available (1-8 or 1-4) for quick use of the items in the slots. \"Diablo II\" added the ability to expand the initial four slots by equipping better &lt;a href=\"belts\"&gt;belts&lt;/a&gt;, providing more space and a mechanism to replenish slots automatically.\nBelt slots represent the concept of a \"utility belt\" with multiple items strapped to it for quick access.\nBelt slots did not return for subsequent games, which significantly reduced the emphasis on consumable items.\nDiablo.\nIn the first game, 8 belt slots are available, used with keys 1-8. Another hotkey uses health or mana potions chosen automatically, first from the inventory and then from the belt. Belts themselves are not an obtainable item type in this game.\nDiablo II.\nThe second game reduced the number of hotkeyed slots to four, used with keys 1-4. However, in addition to the \"bottom\" four belt slots showing in the interface most of the time, additional rows or levels of belt slots can be obtained with &lt;a href=\"belts\"&gt;belts&lt;/a&gt; equipped, with higher quality belts providing more additional rows. Replacement items can then be queued up in additional slots \"above\" the main four, which \"fall\" one by one into the hotkeyed slots when the previous item in that slot is consumed.\nA player may have one to four rows of belt slots with each row providing space for four items, and lengthening the queue of replacements for each slot by one. For example, with three rows of belt slots total, the player has 12 slots total, and may have a health potion prepared in slot 1 with two more prepared \"above\" it. Pressing 1 three times would consume all the potions, at which point that slot would be empty.\nThe number of rows available depends on the currently equipped &lt;a href=\"Belts\"&gt;belt&lt;/a&gt;, with the number of belt slot rows generally increasing with item level. &lt;a href=\"Plated%20Belt\"&gt;Plated Belt&lt;/a&gt;s are the first available belt that provides 4 rows of belt slots."}
{"id": "50580", "revid": "50366882", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=50580", "title": "Beltram", "text": "Beltram was part of &lt;a href=\"Wortham%20Guard\"&gt;Wortham Guard&lt;/a&gt;. He was injured in battle when the &lt;a href=\"Cult%20of%20Damnation\"&gt;Cult of Damnation&lt;/a&gt; attacked &lt;a href=\"Wortham\"&gt;Wortham&lt;/a&gt; western gate. His friends retreated with him. After all was over, they asked &lt;a href=\"the%20Shard-seeker\"&gt;the adventurer who saved the day&lt;/a&gt; for help, but by then Beltram was already dead.\nIn-game.\nBeltram is an &lt;a href=\"NPC\"&gt;NPC&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20Immortal\"&gt;Diablo Immortal&lt;/a&gt;\". After the , he can be found surrounded by friends in the alley to the west of the chapel. The response the player gives is different for each class, but the message is still the same; it is too late to save Beltram. After that, he's not seen again."}
{"id": "1763", "revid": "25771421", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=1763", "title": "Belts", "text": "Worn around the waist, belts not only serve to increase a character's &lt;a href=\"Defense%20Rating\"&gt;Defense Rating&lt;/a&gt;, they also allow a character to hold more &lt;a href=\"potions\"&gt;potions&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"scrolls\"&gt;scrolls&lt;/a&gt;.\nDiablo I.\nIn Diablo I, belts are not equippable items, but rather a panel where one may put up to 8 scrolls and potions for quick use (1-8 digits on a keyboard). There is also a special button assigned for quick use of health / mana potion, which first uses items from inventory and then from the belt.\nDiablo II.\nBelts are present in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20II\"&gt;Diablo II&lt;/a&gt;\".\nBelts play an important role in a character's survival. Designed to provide quick access to items, most belts contain multiple slots, loops, and cords from which to suspend potions and other vital items. The larger a belt then the more potions and scrolls it can store. Wearing a sash or larger belt expands the initial four-slot capacity of a character's belt by adding one or more extra rows of four slots. While only four slots are normally displayed on the Interface Bar, a player can access the additional slots by highlighting any of the visible belt slots or by pressing the tilde (\"~\") key to toggle the belt open and closed.\nDiablo III.\nBelts return in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\". While they no longer serve to store potions (in game, but still do lore-wise), they offer a high range of protective stats. Offensive stats are only found on Legendary belts.\nIn addition to core stats and all-armor bonuses, Belts can roll increased damage for Primary skills, &lt;a href=\"Life\"&gt;Life&lt;/a&gt; %, Life per second, &lt;a href=\"Defense\"&gt;Armor&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Resistances\"&gt;Resistances&lt;/a&gt;, , and chances to &lt;a href=\"Freeze\"&gt;Freeze&lt;/a&gt; on hit.\ns have their own type of Belts: &lt;a href=\"Mighty%20Belts\"&gt;Mighty Belts&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "37135", "revid": "3423357", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=37135", "title": "Ben Boos", "text": "Been Boos was an artist at &lt;a href=\"Blizzard%20North\"&gt;Blizzard North&lt;/a&gt;. He worked on \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20II\"&gt;Diablo II&lt;/a&gt;\", specifically on the game's environments. Alongside &lt;a href=\"Kris%20Renkewitz\"&gt;Kris Renkewitz&lt;/a&gt;, he and a few other artists made a doomed attempt to make a Blizzard North cinematics team, but the attempt fell through.\nAfter he passed away, the &lt;a href=\"Faithful%20Memory\"&gt;Faithful Memory&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Two-Handed%20Swords\"&gt;two-handed sword&lt;/a&gt; was made in his honor."}
