{"id": "38348", "revid": "58609", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=38348", "title": "Dry Steppes", "text": "The Dry Steppes is a geographic area in &lt;a href=\"Sanctuary\"&gt;Sanctuary&lt;/a&gt;, located south of &lt;a href=\"Scosglen\"&gt;Scosglen&lt;/a&gt;, west from the &lt;a href=\"Fractured%20Peaks\"&gt;Fractured Peaks&lt;/a&gt;, and north of &lt;a href=\"Kehjistan\"&gt;Kehjistan&lt;/a&gt;.\nLore.\nThe Dry Steppes are a harsh and rugged wilderness, consisting of amber grasslands, deep canyons, and wide salt flats dotted with geysers of boiling water. Vegetation is rare, and what vegetation there is consists of &lt;a href=\"https%3A//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Populus\"&gt;poplar&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"https%3A//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haloxylon_ammodendron\"&gt;saxaul trees&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe Steppes are an incredibly dangerous place to live, and only the most ruthless or most desperate call them home.\nA variety of beliefs exist(ed) in the Dry Steppes. These include elements of wind worship (e.g. \"wind favor you\") ancestor worship (e.g. \"Ancestors keep you\"), and polytheistic worship (e.g. \"oh gods\"). Some believe that spirits haunt the Steppes, calling out to the living through the &lt;a href=\"Crag%20Song\"&gt;Crag Song&lt;/a&gt;. Old folklore in the Steppes states that &lt;a href=\"khazra\"&gt;khazra&lt;/a&gt; bones ward off curses. In the past, some willingly offered themselves to the pools of &lt;a href=\"the%20Boiling%20Plains\"&gt;the Boiling Plains&lt;/a&gt; as an act of ritual suicide. The Steppes' conception of an afterlife involves/involved \"the plains beyond.\" In ancient times, a being known as the &lt;a href=\"Grinning%20One\"&gt;Grinning One&lt;/a&gt; was worshipped.\nTerrifying effigies are a common sight in the Steppes, built as offerings to appease great evil. To dress oneself in their image is to invite their fury.\nHistory.\nEarly History.\nThe Dry Steppes gave rise to native civilization(s). They were once ruled by the &lt;a href=\"Overseers\"&gt;Overseers&lt;/a&gt;; a line of slaver kings who ruled out of &lt;a href=\"Guulrahn\"&gt;Guulrahn&lt;/a&gt;. Even long after their end, their relics remained spread across the Steppes, leaving suffering in their wake.\nAt some point, &lt;a href=\"Zakarum\"&gt;Zakarum&lt;/a&gt; established a presence in the region. The Zakarum architecture was more distinct and refined than the native one, and in addition to &lt;a href=\"Orbei%20Monastery\"&gt;Orbei Monastery&lt;/a&gt;, established a number of storage and keep-sake areas. \nThe &lt;a href=\"Sons%20of%20Rakkis\"&gt;Sons of Rakkis&lt;/a&gt; marched across the &lt;a href=\"Dry%20Steppes\"&gt;Dry Steppes&lt;/a&gt; during the &lt;a href=\"Zakarum%20Crusade\"&gt;Zakarum Crusade&lt;/a&gt;, and set sail from &lt;a href=\"the%20Scarred%20Coast\"&gt;the Scarred Coast&lt;/a&gt;. By this point, &lt;a href=\"undead\"&gt;undead&lt;/a&gt; roamed the coast, and the &lt;a href=\"Paladin\"&gt;Paladin&lt;/a&gt;s did what they could to cull the undead. In the end, they only served to add to the undead's number.\nBy the time of the &lt;a href=\"Zakarum%20Inquisition\"&gt;Zakarum Inquisition&lt;/a&gt;, the church had effectively annexed the Steppes (or at least part of them), and the &lt;a href=\"Hand%20of%20Zakarum\"&gt;Hand of Zakarum&lt;/a&gt; oversaw the &lt;a href=\"Dindai%20Flats\"&gt;Dindai Flats&lt;/a&gt;. \"Heresy\" was rooted out through violent means, much to the anger and grief of the locals. In some cases, entire villages were left in ruins, and it appears that some of the locals were converted to worship of the &lt;a href=\"Light\"&gt;Light&lt;/a&gt;, willingly or otherwise.\nAfter the destruction of &lt;a href=\"Mount%20Arreat\"&gt;Mount Arreat&lt;/a&gt;, a splinter group of the &lt;a href=\"Oxen%20Tribe\"&gt;Oxen Tribe&lt;/a&gt; made their way into the Steppes. The city of &lt;a href=\"Ked%20Bardu\"&gt;Ked Bardu&lt;/a&gt; grew around their encampment. Similarly, with Zakarum having collapsed, the town of Jirandai was built on the ruins of Zakarum's old empire.\nThe Great Enmity.\nBy the &lt;a href=\"Great%20Enmity\"&gt;Great Enmity&lt;/a&gt;, the Steppes were ravaged by war due to the power vacuum &lt;a href=\"Malthael\"&gt;Malthael&lt;/a&gt; created when he decimated Sanctuary. The Zakarum's storage sites and keep-sakes were laid to waste, and Orbei Monastery fell into ruin.\nMany years ago, the &lt;a href=\"Cannibals\"&gt;Cannibals&lt;/a&gt; appeared in the Steppes and spread their terror into lands beyond. Conflict engulfed the Steppes as s and &lt;a href=\"Druid\"&gt;Druid&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Steppewardens\"&gt;Steppewardens&lt;/a&gt; fought against the Cannibals. The conflict did not end in the Steppes' favor, as the Cannibals remained present in the Steppes, and remained in perpetual conflict with the &lt;a href=\"Crane%20Tribe\"&gt;Crane Tribe&lt;/a&gt;.\nOther groups still operated within the Steppes, trying to win the hearts and minds of the people living there. With &lt;a href=\"Lilith\"&gt;Lilith&lt;/a&gt;'s return, the darker side of mankind became more dominant, and many in the Steppes gave into it, giving into the darkness for more power and turning to cannibalism. The &lt;a href=\"Triune\"&gt;Triune&lt;/a&gt;, which now served Lilith, marched across the Steppes and took a number of unfortunates and brought them to &lt;a href=\"Mount%20Civo\"&gt;Mount Civo&lt;/a&gt;, where they were slaughtered. Others willingly joined the Triune, as the cult promised an escape from their suffering. The Triune also burnt trading caravans.\nAt/around the time of Lilith's return, the situation in the Steppes was further deteriorating. In the north, wasp attacks caused farmers to flee their fields and enter &lt;a href=\"Farobru\"&gt;Farobru&lt;/a&gt;. In the west, bandits blocked the pass to the south of &lt;a href=\"Ked%20Bardu\"&gt;Ked Bardu&lt;/a&gt;, which meant that merchants stayed inside the city. &lt;a href=\"Guulrahn\"&gt;Guulrahn&lt;/a&gt; fell to the Cannibals, the survivors fleeing to Ked Bardu. &lt;a href=\"Jirandai\"&gt;Jirandai&lt;/a&gt; managed to keep the Cannibals at bay, but at heavy cost, and rumors spread of secret Cannibals lurking in towns.\nRecent Events.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Malignant\"&gt;Malignant&lt;/a&gt; spread to the Dry Steppes after Lilith's defeat, encroaching on &lt;a href=\"town\"&gt;town&lt;/a&gt;s with each passing day. was entrusted by &lt;a href=\"Cormond\"&gt;Cormond&lt;/a&gt; to hold them at bay while he searched for a cure. The &lt;a href=\"Malignant%20Tunnels\"&gt;Malignant Tunnels&lt;/a&gt; in the Steppes were cleared out by the Wanderer, and ultimately, the Malignant were wiped out.\nLater, &lt;a href=\"Zir\"&gt;Zir&lt;/a&gt; ordered the &lt;a href=\"Blood%20Seekers\"&gt;Blood Seekers&lt;/a&gt; and their &lt;a href=\"vampire\"&gt;vampire&lt;/a&gt; forces to &lt;a href=\"Blood%20Harvest\"&gt;conquer&lt;/a&gt; the Dry Steppes.\nIn-game.\nThe Dry Steppes are one of six main geographic areas that can be explored in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20IV\"&gt;Diablo IV&lt;/a&gt;\".\nDevelopment.\nInitially, the Steppes were conceived as grasslands. The decision was made to add dark rocks that complement the pale blonde and rusty grasses. To help provide extra visual interest in the region, the Environment Art team created a salt flats biome.\nNotable Locations.\n\"Main article: \nRegions.\nThe Dry Steppes are divided into the following major regions:"}
