{"id": "42484", "revid": "58609", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=42484", "title": "Dungeon", "text": "The term dungeon may refer to:"}
{"id": "42485", "revid": "58609", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=42485", "title": "Dungeon (Diablo IV)", "text": "Dungeons are a gameplay feature of \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20IV\"&gt;Diablo IV&lt;/a&gt;\".\nOverview.\nDungeons remain randomized, similar to previous titles. New features have been implemented, such as seamless floor transitions, as well as transition scenes. These are scenes that allow the developers to connect two different tile-sets together in the same dungeon, while keeping it randomized. Dungeons are designed to feel congruent with the world, that these are structures that exist for a reason. Their aesthetics reflect the zone they're found in (sand-filled dungeons in &lt;a href=\"Kehjistan\"&gt;Kehjistan&lt;/a&gt; for instance).\nOver 150 dungeons feature in the game. Some dungeons are tied to the game's main storyline, others to side quests. However, the majority of dungeons are self-contained in terms of plot. Some \"mini dungeons\" exist that are only one room. Some dungeons are story-exclusive, and can only be played once.\nCompleting a dungeon grants the player &lt;a href=\"renown\"&gt;renown&lt;/a&gt;.\nSome &lt;a href=\"stronghold\"&gt;stronghold&lt;/a&gt;s become dungeons after being cleared out the first time. After completing the game's main quest, players will gain access to \"Nightmare Dungeons.\" These are remixed versions of dungeons, filled with stronger &lt;a href=\"monster\"&gt;monster&lt;/a&gt;s, new objectives, and other afflictions. Upon completion, each dungeon grants the player an &lt;a href=\"aspect\"&gt;aspect&lt;/a&gt;; each aspect is unique to the dungeon it is found in.\nDungeons are solitary experiences, though may be completed as part of a party. Each dungeon has a recommended &lt;a href=\"character%20level\"&gt;level&lt;/a&gt;.\nIn the game's zone map, dungeons are marked by an iron gate icon.\nDevelopment.\nThe dungeons in \"Diablo IV\" were developed by the \"dungeon team.\""}
{"id": "39881", "revid": "2011810", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=39881", "title": "Dungeon (Diablo Immortal)", "text": "Dungeons are a gameplay feature of \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20Immortal\"&gt;Diablo Immortal&lt;/a&gt;\". They are instanced, four-player experiences. Each dungeon has a specific number of &lt;a href=\"monsters\"&gt;monsters&lt;/a&gt; and a selection of &lt;a href=\"boss\"&gt;boss&lt;/a&gt;es. They are designed to be completed quickly, and are intended for groups of players, though can be completed solo. They are expected to take players 10\u201315 minutes to complete (in reality they can be done in a few minutes). Multiple difficulties are available. Each boss has items unique to their loot table.\nDungeons can be queued from anywhere. A &lt;a href=\"blacksmith\"&gt;blacksmith&lt;/a&gt; is located at the end of each dungeon. Dungeons have a chance to drop a &lt;a href=\"set%20item\"&gt;set item&lt;/a&gt;, with a guaranteed drop after at most every 7 runs if using the Random Dungeon finder.\nDungeons feature a damage statistics tracker that shows the breakdown of damage done per skill.\n&lt;a href=\"Helliquary\"&gt;Helliquary&lt;/a&gt; zones are regarded as dungeon in some respects, though are practically just single boss arenas and don't use many of the mechanics associated with the dungeons described on this page (which are sometimes referred to as daily dungeons to be specific).\nRandom Dungeon.\nThe Random Dungeon feature allows entering into any dungeon that is looking for a party. It can be found by opening the Party Finder from the menu (not by opening the party view using the icon next to the character portrait). It can also be opened from the Codex, but only if there is no &lt;a href=\"Battle%20Points\"&gt;Battle Point&lt;/a&gt; reward to claim, as the Claim button replaces the search button. When accepting the party, the Random Dungeon entry animation crossfades into the entry animation of the dungeon chosen, and then the dungeon loads. Completing a dungeon via Random Dungeon adds a pity counter that guarantees a &lt;a href=\"Set%20Items\"&gt;Set Item&lt;/a&gt; after at most 7 dungeons. The counter will only appear if there was no set item dropped using the normal drop mechanics, and is reset to zero after a set item drops in either way. A set item drop from the chest (as opposed to the boss) will not reset the counter.\nWarp to Final Boss.\nStarting with the &lt;a href=\"Splintered%20Souls\"&gt;Splintered Souls&lt;/a&gt; update, a portal may appear during a dungeon. This instantly warps players to the final boss, but the boss will be stronger than regular. It also increases rewards and &lt;a href=\"Treasure%20Goblin\"&gt;Treasure Goblin&lt;/a&gt;s may spawn. This modifier was called \"Greed's Spoils\" in the patch notes but this name is not used in the game, instead the popup window has the label \"Warp to Final Boss\" under the icon.\nChallenge Dungeon.\nThe Challenge Dungeon option (available at Inferno I or higher) increases the difficulty of the dungeon for the chance of better rewards. There is a weekly reward containing a &lt;a href=\"Set%20Item\"&gt;Set Item&lt;/a&gt; for clearing a Challenge Dungeon, and the drop rates for regular rewards is increased.\nMonsters have 300% more Life and deal 200% more damage in Challenge Dungeons. Additionally, one or two of the following modifiers are applied:\nHistory.\nTristram Cathedral and the Random Dungeon feature were added in the September 21 2023 update.\nThe update added the ability to vote to kick a player from Random Dungeons.\nThe damage tracker was added in the update.\nChallenge Dungeons were added in the update."}
