{"id": "29045", "revid": "24916843", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=29045", "title": "Progress Globe", "text": ""}
{"id": "29821", "revid": "1773829", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=29821", "title": "Progress globe", "text": ""}
{"id": "50463", "revid": "50366882", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=50463", "title": "Progress orb", "text": "Progress orbs are objects that appear in a &lt;a href=\"Nephalem%20Rift\"&gt;Nephalem&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Greater%20Rift\"&gt;Greater Rift&lt;/a&gt; upon defeating a &lt;a href=\"Champion%20Monster\"&gt;Champion Monster&lt;/a&gt; pack or &lt;a href=\"Rare%20Monster\"&gt;Rare Monster&lt;/a&gt;, which increase the progress bar of the rift by 1% when collected, hastening the summoning of the &lt;a href=\"Rift%20Guardian\"&gt;Rift Guardian&lt;/a&gt;. Three or four orbs are dropped normally, and a fifth drops when the Reaper seal of the &lt;a href=\"Altar%20of%20Rites\"&gt;Altar of Rites&lt;/a&gt; is unlocked in &lt;a href=\"season\"&gt;season&lt;/a&gt;al play. They make killing &lt;a href=\"Elite%20Monsters\"&gt;Elite Monsters&lt;/a&gt; a reliable tactic for clearing rifts, and consequently some strategies focus solely on elites.\nThe orbs appear in the game world and must be collected by moving close to them. &lt;a href=\"Affix\"&gt;Item bonuses&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Paragon\"&gt;Paragon&lt;/a&gt; points improving the \"Gold and Health Pickup radius\" also apply to progress orbs, and the Reach seal of the Altar of Rites allows near-automatic collection (within 60 yards). Using in Rifts leverages the progress orb mechanic by generating extra elite packs from &lt;a href=\"Pylon\"&gt;Pylon&lt;/a&gt;s - these packs drop the same amount of progress orbs as any other elite pack.\nRegular progress orbs drop from the last &lt;a href=\"Champion%20Monster\"&gt;Champion Monster&lt;/a&gt; of a pack, or from a &lt;a href=\"Rare%20Monster\"&gt;Rare Monster&lt;/a&gt; even if its minions are \"not\" killed. However the extra orb from the Altar of Rites Reaper seal only drops when the full pack is killed \"including\" minions, much like the &lt;a href=\"Legendary%20Gem\"&gt;Legendary Gem&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe progress orbs of the two types of rifts work the same, although Nephalem Rift orbs are golden orange, while Greater Rift orbs are purple. Both are slightly hazy looking and have skulls in the center, presumably representing the essence of the elite monster(s) killed.\n&lt;a href=\"Health%20Globe\"&gt;Health Globe&lt;/a&gt;s and progress orbs bear some resemblance as proximity-collected objects that appear upon defeating powerful monsters. However progress orbs have a much more strict and predictable pattern within the gameplay, and they have completely different benefits. Special powers or bonuses work only on one or the other and not both, with the exception of Pickup radius increases. \nIn \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20Immortal\"&gt;Diablo Immortal&lt;/a&gt;\", s appear in the &lt;a href=\"Challenge%20Rift\"&gt;Challenge Rift&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Elder%20Rift\"&gt;Elder Rift&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "37654", "revid": "58609", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=37654", "title": "Project Fenris", "text": ""}
{"id": "37653", "revid": "58609", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=37653", "title": "Project Hades", "text": "Project Hades was the codename for a cancelled \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20series\"&gt;Diablo&lt;/a&gt;\" title.\nGameplay.\nAccording to three people who worked on the project, Hades would have been a \"Diablo\" game in the style of \"&lt;a href=\"https%3A//darksouls.wikia.com/wiki/Dark_Souls\"&gt;Dark Souls&lt;/a&gt;\". According to other sources, Hades took inspiration from the combat of the \"&lt;a href=\"https%3A//arkhamcity.fandom.com/wiki/Arkham_Wiki\"&gt;Batman: Arkham&lt;/a&gt;\" games. It would be a Gothic, challenging dungeon crawler, utilizing a third person over-the-shoulder camera rather than the series's traditional isometric design. It has also been described as a roguelike with a permadeath system for every run. Perks accumulated by the character in their run would be transferred to the next created character. The game would feature cooperative multiplayer.\nDevelopment.\nWork on Project Hades began after the release of \"&lt;a href=\"Reaper%20of%20Souls\"&gt;Reaper of Souls&lt;/a&gt;\" and the cancellation of \"&lt;a href=\"The%20King%20in%20the%20North\"&gt;The King in the North&lt;/a&gt;\". The original mandate was for &lt;a href=\"Team%203\"&gt;Team 3&lt;/a&gt; to create a \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20IV\"&gt;Diablo IV&lt;/a&gt;,\" regardless of what form such a game would take. The project was overseen by &lt;a href=\"Josh%20Mosqueira\"&gt;Josh Mosqueira&lt;/a&gt;, who prototyped the concept. At the time, Mosqueira was seen as \"Blizzard's golden boy,\" and &lt;a href=\"Mike%20Morhaime\"&gt;Mike Morhaime&lt;/a&gt; wanted him to create a fourth \"Diablo\" game as quickly as possible.\nAfter years of working on the \"Diablo\" series, Mosqueira wanted to try something completely new. He gathered a few artists and designers and began conceptualizing the game.\nFrom 2014 until 2016, Hades was Team 3's main project, developed alongside a handful of patches and light content updates for \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\". However, Team 3 ran into difficulties almost immediately. One of the problems was its combat system. While it took after \"Batman: Arkham\", those were singleplayer games, and it was hard to transpose it into a multiplayer game. For instance, in \"Arkham\", a time dilation mechanic features\u2014how would this affect two characters? Tean 3 designers began to wonder whether this was really \"Diablo\" anymore, and it was such a departure from the prior games, some at Blizzard thought they might not even end up calling it \"Diablo IV.\"\nAnother issue was the game's use of staff. Hades only required a small subset of Team 3, and the remaining developers found themselves with little else to do. A few of them began calling themselves \"Team Summer Camp\" in an echo of what had happened at &lt;a href=\"Blizzard%20North\"&gt;Blizzard North&lt;/a&gt; many years earlier. People would arrive at work, play \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\", have lunch, head home, etc. As some of the \"Summer Camp\" team moved to the Hades team, the pressure grew on Mosqueira to make decisions so they'd have something to do. However, Mosqueira became harder to track down, coming in to the office only two or three days a week, which hampered some of the designers\u2019 progress as they waited for feedback.\nMosqueira announced he was leaving Blizzard in July, 2016. When a group of Blizzard executives and lead designers came to evaluate the progress of Hades, they left unimpressed. Believing that the project wouldn\u2019t be feasible without Mosqueira, they decided to cancel it. Diablo IV would have to start from scratch. When asked in 2018, Mosqueira refused to comment on the project.\nThe cancellation of Hades led to Team 3 splitting between two projects. The first was \"&lt;a href=\"Rise%20of%20the%20Necromancer\"&gt;Rise of the Necromancer&lt;/a&gt;\", which they hoped would act as a short-term solution for fans hungry for more \"Diablo\" content. The second group began worked on &lt;a href=\"Project%20Fenris\"&gt;Project Fenris&lt;/a&gt;. As Project Hades had never been publicaly announced, this led to a lull in \"Diablo\" releases, leading some fans to wonder why the franchise appeared dormant. "}
